>1</center>\n| [[Akademija Pandev]] (1)\n|}\n\n== Republic Cup ==\n{|\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| \n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=50 |Season\n! width=200|Champion\n|-\n| 1946\u201347 || Garnizon Skopje\n|-\n| 1947\u201348 || [[FK Teteks]] \n|-\n| 1948\u201349 || ''unknown''\n|-\n| 1949\u201350 || [[FK Teteks]]\n|-\n| 1950\u201351 || [[FK Pobeda]]\n|-\n| 1951\u201352 || Garnizon Skopje\n|-\n| 1952\u201353 || [[FK Vardar]] 2nd team or B-squad\n|-\n| 1953\u201354 || [[FK Rabotni\u010dki|FK Rabotnichki]] \n|-\n| 1954\u201355 || [[FK Vardar]]\n|-\n| 1955\u201356 || ''not held''\n|-\n| 1956\u201357 || [[FK Rabotni\u010dki|FK Rabotnichki]]\n|-\n| 1957\u201358 || [[FK Pobeda]]\n|-\n| 1958\u201359 || [[FK Pelister]] \n|-\n| 1959\u201360 || [[FK Pobeda]] \n|-\n| 1960\u201361 || [[FK Pobeda]] \n|-\n| 1961\u201362 || [[FK Pelister]]\n|-\n| 1962\u201363 || [[FK Pobeda]]\n|-\n| 1963\u201364 || [[FK Pobeda]]\n|-\n| 1964\u201365 || [[FK Vardar]]\n|-\n| 1965\u201366 || [[FK Vardar]] \n|-\n| 1966\u201367 || [[FK Vardar]] \n|-\n| 1967\u201368 || [[FK Vardar]] \n|-\n| 1968\u201369 || [[FK Vardar]]\n|}\n|\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=50 |Season\n! width=200|Champion\n|-\n| 1969\u201370 || [[FK Vardar]]\n|-\n| 1970\u201371 || [[FK Vardar]]\n|-\n| 1971\u201372 || [[FK Vardar]]\n|-\n| 1972\u201373 || [[FK Ohrid]]\n|-\n| 1973\u201374 || [[FK Rabotni\u010dki|FK Rabotnichki]]\n|-\n| 1974\u201375 || ''not held''\n|-\n| 1975\u201376 || [[FK Vardar]] 2nd team or B-squad\n|-\n| 1976\u201377 || [[FK Pobeda]]\n|-\n| 1977\u201378 || [[FK Teteks]]\n|-\n| 1978\u201379 || [[FK Vardar]]\n|-\n| 1979\u201380 || [[FK Vardar]]\n|-\n| 1980\u201381 || [[FK Bregalnica \u0160tip|FK Bregalnica]]\n|-\n| 1981\u201382 || [[FK Teteks]]\n|-\n| 1982\u201383 || [[FK Rabotni\u010dki|FK Rabotnichki]]\n|-\n| 1983\u201384 || [[FK Belasica]]\n|-\n| 1984\u201385 || [[FK Pelister]]\n|-\n| 1985\u201386 || [[FK Belasica]]\n|-\n| 1986\u201387 || [[FK Pobeda]]\n|-\n| 1987\u201388 || [[FK Rabotni\u010dki|FK Rabotnichki]]\n|-\n| 1988\u201389 || [[FK Sileks]]\n|-\n| 1989\u201390 || [[FK Sileks]]\n|-\n| 1990\u201391 || [[FK Pelister]]\n|-\n| 1991\u201392 || [[FK Vardar]]\n|-\n|}\n|}\nSource:<ref>{{cite web|title=Mazedonischer Pokal|url=http://www.spitzerwinkel.de/Europa/Ligen/Mazedonien/info/Pokal.html|publisher=spitzerwinkel.de|accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{refbegin}}\n:A.&nbsp;{{note|Sloga}} The Sloga Jugomagnat, which traced its roots back to 1927 went excluded after a missing two games in the 2009\u201310 season and folded in 2009. In 2012, a successor club called FK Shkupi was founded after a merger with FK Albarsa which started in the 3rd League. The club won first place in the 2012\u201313 season and after was a failed to promote to the 2nd League, the club was a merged with FK Korzo and a placed in the 2nd League for the 2013\u201314 season (in fall season was played as Korzo). However, despite club officials and fans claims that the Shkupi is the Sloga Jugomagnat's successor, neither the Football Federation of Macedonia nor UEFA recognize Sloga Jugomagnat's titles and statistics before 2009 as being part of the 2012 founded Shkupi's track record.\n{{refend}}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n:B.&nbsp;{{note|Pobeda}} The original Pobeda, which was traced its roots back to 1941 went banned from UEFA competitions in 2010 and will be eligible in the 2017\u201318 season. In 2010, a successor club called FK Viktorija (later renamed to Pobeda Junior) was founded which started competing in the 3rd league. Despite club officials and fans claims that the new Pobeda Junior is the Pobeda's successor, neither the Football Federation of Macedonia nor UEFA recognize Pobeda's titles and statistics before 2010 as being part of the 2010 founded Pobeda Junior's track record.\n{{refend}}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n:C.&nbsp;{{note|Bashkimi}} The original Bashkimi, which was traced its roots back to 1947 went bankrupt and folded in 2008. In 2011, a successor club called FK Bashkimi 1947 was founded which started competing in the 3rd league. Despite club officials and fans claims that the new Bashkimi is the defunct club's successor, neither the Football Federation of Macedonia nor UEFA recognize Bashkimi's titles and statistics before 2008 as being part of the 2011-founded Bashkimi's track record.\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://ffm.mk/ Football Federation of Macedonia] {{in lang|mk|en}}\n*[http://www.macedonianfootball.com MacedonianFootball.com] {{in lang|en}}\n\n{{Macedonian Football Cup seasons}}\n{{Football in the Republic of Macedonia}}\n{{National football Cups (UEFA region)}}\n\n[[Category:Macedonian Football Cup| ]]\n[[Category:Football competitions in North Macedonia|Cup]]\n[[Category:National association football cups|Macedonia]]\n[[Category:1992 establishments in the Republic of Macedonia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{infobox football tournament\n| current = [[2019\u201320 Macedonian Football Cup]]\n| logo = [[File:Macedonian Football Cup logo.jpg|120px]]\n| founded = 1992\n| number of teams = c.\u200932\n| region = {{nowrap|{{MKD}}}}\n| qualifier for = [[UEFA Europa League]]\n| current champions = [[Akademija Pandev]]<br />(1st&nbsp;title)\n| most successful club = [[FK Vardar|Vardar]]<br />(5&nbsp;titles)\n| website = [http://ffm.mk/ ffm.mk]\n}}\n\nThe '''Macedonian Football Cup''' ({{lang-mk|\u041a\u0443\u043f \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430}}, ''Kup na Makedonija''), is the top knockout tournament of Macedonian [[Association football|football]] and is the second most important football competition in [[North Macedonia]] after the [[First Macedonian Football League|Macedonian First League]] championship. The cup was established in 1992 after local clubs had abandoned the [[Yugoslav First League]] and [[Yugoslav Cup]] competitions following the [[breakup of Yugoslavia]].\n\nAs of 2014, a total of 16 clubs have reached the cup finals and the most successful side in the history of the competition is [[FK Vardar|Vardar]], who have triumphed 5 times in their 6 cup final appearances.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vardar wins the Macedonian Cup|url=http://macedonianfootball.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=39:vardar-wins-the-macedonian-cup&catid=1:domestic&Itemid=63|publisher=macedonianfootball.com|accessdate=26 May 2007}}</ref> They are followed by [[FK Rabotni\u010dki|Rabotni\u010dki]] and [[FK Sloga Jugomagnat|Sloga Jugomagnat]], who have won 4 titles.\n\n== Winners ==\n[[File:Mac. Cup logo.PNG|thumbnail|right|Macedonian Cup's former logo]]\n\n'''Key'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#cedff2\"|\u2020\n|Match decided by a [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] after [[extra time]]\n|-\n|align=center style=\"background-color:#fff4a7\"|{{double dagger}}\n|Winning team won '''[[Double (association football)|The Double]]'''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Season\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"140\"|Winner\n!scope=\"col\"|Score\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"140\"|Runners\u2013up\n!scope=\"col\"|Venue\n!scope=\"col\"|Attendance\n|-\n|align=center|[[1992\u201393 Macedonian Football Cup|1992\u201393]]\n!scope=row style=\"background-color:#fff4a7\"| [[FK Vardar|Vardar]] {{double dagger}} (1)\n|align=center|1\u20130\n|[[FK Pelister|Pelister]]\n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|20,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[1993\u201394 Macedonian Football Cup|1993\u201394]]\n!scope=row|[[FK Sileks|Sileks]] (1)\n|align=center style=\"background-color:#cedff2\"|1\u20131 ([[Overtime (sports)|a.e.t.]]), <br> 4\u20132 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|pen.]]\n|[[FK Pelister|Pelister]]\n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center| \n|-\n|align=center|[[1994\u201395 Macedonian Football Cup|1994\u201395]]\n!scope=row style=\"background-color:#fff4a7\"| [[FK Vardar|Vardar]] {{double dagger}} (2)\n|align=center|2\u20131\n|[[FK Sileks|Sileks]] \n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|20,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[1995\u201396 Macedonian Football Cup|1995\u201396]]\n!scope=row|[[FK Sloga Jugomagnat|Sloga Jugomagnat]] (1)\n|align=center style=\"background-color:#cedff2\"|0\u20130 ([[Overtime (sports)|a.e.t.]]), <br> 5\u20133 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|pen.]]\n|[[FK Vardar|Vardar]]\n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|18,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[1996\u201397 Macedonian Football Cup|1996\u201397]]\n!scope=row style=\"background-color:#fff4a7\"| [[FK Sileks|Sileks]] {{double dagger}} (2)\n|align=center|4\u20131\n|[[FK Sloga Jugomagnat|Sloga Jugomagnat]] \n|[[Gradski Stadion Kavadarci|Gradski stadion]], [[Kavadarci]]\n|align=center|4,500\n|-\n|align=center|[[1997\u201398 Macedonian Football Cup|1997\u201398]]\n!scope=row|[[FK Vardar|Vardar]] (3)\n|align=center|2\u20130\n|[[FK Sloga Jugomagnat|Sloga Jugomagnat]] \n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|19,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[1998\u201399 Macedonian Football Cup|1998\u201399]]\n!scope=row|[[FK Vardar|Vardar]] (4)\n|align=center|2\u20130\n|[[FK Sloga Jugomagnat|Sloga Jugomagnat]]\n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|14,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[1999\u20132000 Macedonian Football Cup|1999\u201300]]\n!scope=row style=\"background-color:#fff4a7\"| [[FK Sloga Jugomagnat|Sloga Jugomagnat]] {{double dagger}} (2)\n|align=center|6\u20130\n|[[FK Pobeda|Pobeda]]\n|[[Stadion Goce Del\u010dev|Stadion Goce Delchev]], [[Prilep]]\n|align=center|12,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[2000\u201301 Macedonian Football Cup|2000\u201301]]\n!scope=row|[[FK Pelister|Pelister]] (1)\n|align=center|2\u20131\n|[[FK Sloga Jugomagnat|Sloga Jugomagnat]]\n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|5,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[2001\u201302 Macedonian Football Cup|2001\u201302]]\n!scope=row|[[FK Pobeda|Pobeda]] (1)\n|align=center|3\u20131\n|[[FK Cementarnica 55|Cementarnica 55]]\n|[[Stadion Mladost, Strumica|Stadion Mladost]], [[Strumica]]\n|align=center|6,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[2002\u201303 Macedonian Football Cup|2002\u201303]]\n!scope=row|[[FK Cementarnica 55|Cementarnica 55]] (1)\n|align=center style=\"background-color:#cedff2\"|4\u20134 ([[Overtime (sports)|a.e.t.]]), <br> 3\u20132 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|pen.]]\n|[[FK Sloga Jugomagnat|Sloga Jugomagnat]]\n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|7,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[2003\u201304 Macedonian Football Cup|2003\u201304]]\n!scope=row|[[FK Sloga Jugomagnat|Sloga Jugomagnat]] (3)\n|align=center|1\u20130\n|[[FK Napredok|Napredok]]\n|[[Philip II Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|5,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[2004\u201305 Macedonian Football Cup|2004\u201305]]\n!scope=row|[[KF Bashkimi (1947\u20132008)|Bashkimi]] (1)\n|align=center|2\u20131\n|[[FK Mad\u017eari Solidarnost|Madjari Solidarnost]]\n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|10,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[2005\u201306 Macedonian Football Cup|2005\u201306]]\n!scope=row|[[FK Makedonija Gjor\u010de Petrov|Makedonija GP]] (1)\n|align=center|3\u20132\n|[[KF Shk\u00ebndija|Shk\u00ebndija]]\n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|14,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[2006\u201307 Macedonian Football Cup|2006\u201307]]\n!scope=row|[[FK Vardar|Vardar]] (5)\n|align=center|2\u20131\n|[[FK Pobeda|Pobeda]]\n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|5,000\n|-\n|align=center|[[2007\u201308 Macedonian Football Cup|2007\u201308]]\n!scope=row style=\"background-color:#fff4a7\"| [[FK Rabotni\u010dki|Rabotnichki]] {{double dagger}} (1)\n|align=center|2\u20130\n|[[KF Milano Kumanov\u00eb|Milano]]\n|[[To\u0161e Proeski Arena|Gradski stadion]], [[Skopje]]\n|align=center|5,